2.body:
To begin this C++ journey, we are going to look at the classic Hello World program. Regardless of your experience with other languages, this will look pretty foreign, so it is worth-while to go through it. import <iostream> int main() { std::cout << "Hello, World!\n";
} There is quite a lot going on in this snippet, so I will break it down into pieces. First, the import statement at the top allows access to the <iostream> "header". Importing these headers grants as access to different parts of the C++ standard library.
2.title: Hello, World

4.body: It then looks up the cout name inside the namespace std. A namespace is what it sounds like, a collection of names. Everything in the C++ standard library is contained inside std, and therefore must be preceded with std::.

6.body:
Variables are names that represent values in the program. They can be declared with the auto keyword. int main() { auto x = 1; // Creates a variable called x with the value 1 std::cout << x << '\n'; x = 2; // Reassigns it to the value 2 std::cout << x << '\n';
} Note that by default, variables are auto
6.title: Variables
